# High-Efficiency AI Operating Protocol (SDLC 2026) - Project Rules

## 1. Core Technical Stack
- Framework: .NET 8 / C# 12
- Architecture: Clean Architecture / Domain-Driven Design (DDD)
- DI: Always use Constructor Injection.
- Async: Enforce 'Async' all the way down; avoid .Result or .Wait().

## 2. Manufacturing Logic & Domain Standards
- Domain: Manufacturing Execution Systems (MES).
- Patterns: Adhere to Siemens Opcenter integration standards.
- Data Integrity: All logic involving machine state must include retry policies (Polly) and idempotency checks.
- Units: Always specify units of measure in variable names (e.g., `temperatureCelsius`, `pressureBar`).

## 3. xUnit & Testing Requirements (MANDATORY)
- Framework: xUnit with Moq and FluentAssertions.
- Structure: One test project per main project. File naming: [ClassName]Tests.cs.
- Requirements: 
    - Every new service must have a corresponding Unit Test.
    - Use the AAA (Arrange, Act, Assert) pattern.
    - Mock all external dependencies (Database, API, PLC connectors).
- Execution: AI must verify code by attempting to run `dotnet test` in the terminal before finalizing a task.

## 4. OpenTelemetry & Observability Standards
- Implementation: Use the OpenTelemetry .NET SDK.
- Spans: Every Service-level method must start a new Activity (Span).
- Tags: Mandatorily include 'manufacturing.line.id', 'user.id', and 'operation.type' in all spans.
- Logging: Use ILogger with structured logging. No `Console.WriteLine`.

## 5. Security & Snyk Guardrails (Tier A/B)
- Secrets: NEVER hardcode connection strings or API keys. Use User Secrets or Environment Variables.
- Vulnerabilities: Before submitting code, the agent should check for "Snyk" highlights in the IDE.
- IP Protection: Do not suggest external libraries without checking if they are pre-approved for manufacturing environments.